<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEALS: COMPANY TOWN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JAMES BATES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Film: Samuel Goldwyn Co. said it has acquired the rights to the 400-title Rank 
Films library, including such classics as David Lean's "Oliver Twist," Laurence 
Olivier's "Hamlet" and Alfred Hitchcock's "The 39 Steps." Terms were not 
disclosed.Goldwyn acquired the North American theatrical, video, television and 
cable rights to the library from Rank Film Distributors Ltd. The acquisition 
creates a 900-title library for Goldwyn, the largest such library in North 
America, according to the company. Goldwyn President Meyer Gottlieb said he 
expects that acquiring the library could account for 5% of the company's 
revenue in fiscal 1997 and boost earnings even more. Rank is the largest 
independent film distributor in Britain. Other movies in the Rank Films library 
include "Great Expectations," "Henry V" and "A Night to Remember." 
</P>
<P>
 * TV: Comsat Corp. and Prime Sports Network are forming a joint venture to 
develop sports and entertainment opportunities. JAMES BATES 
</P>
