<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY ALMANAC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Huntington Beach was rocked by unrest on the Fourth of July as hundreds of 
revelers burned objects and thronged downtown streets. Disturbances resulted in 
clashes with police.Below are some facts and figures released by the city:  
</P>
<P>
 * 183 police officers as well as 30 sergeants, six lieutenants, one captain 
and the police chief worked that night. 
</P>
<P>
 * $171,369.41 was spent for extra police services that night. 
</P>
<P>
 * 222 people were arrested. 
</P>
<P>
 * At least 5,000 gallons of water was sprayed to disperse revelers. Today 
</P>
<P>
 The Corona del Mar Chamber of Commerce will host an open forum for Newport 
Beach City Council candidates and other local office seekers at its monthly 
meeting, which starts at 11:30 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
 The $14 admission includes a noon luncheon. There will be discussions with 
more than 20 candidates for the Newport Beach City Council, Newport-Mesa 
Unified School District board and Coastal Community College District. 
</P>
<P>
 The forum will be at the Five Crowns restaurant, 3801 E. Coast Highway. For 
more information, call the chamber at (714) 673-4050. 
</P>
