<HEADLINE>
<P>
QUAKE-DEBRIS DISPOSAL PLAN DIES; PANORAMA CITY: A FIRM HAS GIVEN UP A PROPOSAL 
TO HAUL RUBBLE TO ITS UTAH LANDFILL BECAUSE OF WAITS FOR CITY PERMITS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By HUGO MARTIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A company that proposed hauling quake debris by rail from the vacant General 
Motors plant in Panorama City has given up on the project because of delays in 
obtaining city permits, a representative of the company said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 ECDC Environmental, a Utah-based waste-disposal firm, had planned to begin 
hauling quake rubble to its 3,000-acre landfill in East Carbon City, Utah, by 
July, said Kent Loest, the firm's vice president for field operations. 
</P>
<P>
 But Loest said the firm was told in June that the city would consider the 
permits under its normal approval process instead of under a quicker emergency 
process approved by the mayor shortly after the Jan. 17 quake. 
</P>
<P>
 "By the time we would have the permits, most of the waste debris would be 
cleared away," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 But Lilian Kawasaki, general manager of the city's Environmental Affairs 
Department, said the death of the project will not have a severe impact on the 
city because local landfills have enough capacity to accept all of the quake 
debris. She added that the city is also vigorously recycling as much of the 
rubble as possible. 
</P>
<P>
 Kawasaki said ECDC and other firms have not given up on the idea of rail haul 
in Los Angeles and are studying sites throughout the region as possible 
rail-haul centers. HUGO MARTIN 
</P>
</TEXT>
