<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEEKEND BOX OFFICE; AN ARRESTING OPENING FOR 'TIMECOP' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BARBARA ISENBERG and ELAINE DUTKA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Despite the usual post-Labor Day slowdown, box-office receipts again topped 
the comparable figures for 1993, as they have every weekend since July 8. 
</P>
<P>
 Universal's "TimeCop" accounted for a little more than one in four tickets 
sold, becoming the first Jean-Claude Van Damme picture to land in first 
place."It's one of the best September openings ever," notes John Krier, 
president of Exhibitor Relations, which tracks box-office performances. 
</P>
<P>
 * Robert Redford's "Quiz Show," a drama based on the 1950s quiz show scandals, 
turned in a strong performance for Disney's Hollywood Pictures in a 13-city 
limited run. This Friday, it will open on 220 more screens nationwide. 
